At individual scale, cross-border volunteering is incorporated in the emerging youth lifestyles and is increasingly viewed as a “rite of passage to adulthood.” At a broader scale, it has been linked with the notion of “global citizenship” (Rovisco, 2009; Smith & Laurie, 2010). Regardless the reasons, it is certain that cross-border volunteering became so much part and parcel of youth transitions that it created a demand for volunteering programs (see the controversies around the new industry of “voluntourism,” and also the stories of exploitation in some volunteering schemes
